<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="389" type="systematic considerations">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="389">Systematic considerations.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="389">
This species seems to be closely related to 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" genus="S." kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="S. brasiliana" order="Trichoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="389" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="brasiliana">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="389">S. brasiliana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" genus="S." kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="S. nanda" order="Trichoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="389" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="nanda">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="389">S. nanda</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(see Systematic considerations section for 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" genus="S." kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="S. brasiliana" order="Trichoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="389" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="brasiliana">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="389">S. brasiliana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
). 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Flint" authorityYear="1972" class="Insecta" family="Hydropsychidae" genus="Smicridea" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Smicridea weidneri" order="Trichoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="389" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="weidneri">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="389">Smicridea weidneri</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
can be identified by the spindle-shaped distal end of the ejaculatory duct, that is simple in the other two species, and the shape of the two pairs of plates, two rhomboidal, with ventral and posterior margins serrated, and covered with small spines, and two spine-like, wide, directed posteriorly.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
